-{"id":"bd-3g28","title":"Fix NTM driver zombie agents on persistent poll failures","description":"# Bug: NTM Driver Creates Zombie Agents on Poll Failures

## Problem Statement
The NTM driver's output polling silently swallows errors. When NTM becomes unavailable or an agent session is deleted in NTM, the Gateway continues to report the agent as "alive" indefinitely.

## Affected File
`packages/agent-drivers/src/ntm/ntm-driver.ts` (lines 358-364, 303-314)

## Current Behavior (BROKEN)
```typescript
// Lines 358-364 - Errors silently logged at debug level
} catch (err) {
  // Don't throw - polling errors are non-fatal
  logDriver("debug", this.driverType, "poll_output_skipped", {
    agentId,
    error: String(err),
  });
}

// Lines 303-314 - Interval never cleared on persistent errors
session.pollInterval = setInterval(() => {
  this.pollOutput(agentId).catch((err) => {
    logDriver("error", this.driverType, "output_poll_error", { agentId, error: String(err) });
  });
}, this.pollIntervalMs);
```

## Impact
- **Zombie agents**: Agents appear active in Gateway but are dead in NTM
- **Resource leak**: Polling intervals continue firing forever
- **Operator confusion**: Monitoring shows healthy agents that aren't responding
- **Wasted resources**: Continuous polling to unavailable NTM

## Root Cause
1. Poll errors are logged at debug level and swallowed
2. No error counting or threshold-based state transition
3. No mechanism to mark agent as failed after repeated poll failures

## Proposed Solution
Implement error counting with automatic state transition:

```typescript
interface NtmAgentSession {
  // ... existing fields
  consecutiveErrors: number;
  lastSuccessfulPoll: Date;
}

const MAX_CONSECUTIVE_ERRORS = 5;
const MAX_POLL_STALE_MS = 60000;  // 1 minute without successful poll

async pollOutput(agentId: string): Promise<void> {
  const session = this.sessions.get(agentId);
  if (!session) return;

  try {
    // ... existing poll logic

    // Reset error counter on success
    session.consecutiveErrors = 0;
    session.lastSuccessfulPoll = new Date();
  } catch (err) {
    session.consecutiveErrors++;

    logDriver("warn", this.driverType, "poll_output_error", {
      agentId,
      error: String(err),
      consecutiveErrors: session.consecutiveErrors,
    });

    if (session.consecutiveErrors >= MAX_CONSECUTIVE_ERRORS) {
      logDriver("error", this.driverType, "poll_failure_threshold_exceeded", {
        agentId,
        consecutiveErrors: session.consecutiveErrors,
      });

      // Transition agent to failed state
      await this.markAgentFailed(agentId, "NTM poll failures exceeded threshold");
    }
  }
}

private async markAgentFailed(agentId: string, reason: string): Promise<void> {
  const session = this.sessions.get(agentId);
  if (!session) return;

  // Clear poll interval
  if (session.pollInterval) {
    clearInterval(session.pollInterval);
    session.pollInterval = undefined;
  }

  // Emit terminated event with error reason
  this.emitEvent(agentId, {
    type: "terminated",
    agentId,
    timestamp: new Date(),
    reason: "error",
    exitCode: 1,
    error: reason,
  });

  // Update state machine
  await this.updateAgentState(agentId, "failed");

  // Cleanup session
  this.sessions.delete(agentId);
}
```

## Implementation Details

### Configuration
Add to NTM driver config:
```typescript
interface NtmDriverConfig {
  maxConsecutivePollErrors?: number;  // Default: 5
  maxPollStaleMs?: number;            // Default: 60000 (1 min)
  pollHealthCheckEnabled?: boolean;    // Default: true
}
```

### State Machine Integration
The NTM driver should notify the agent state machine when marking an agent as failed:
```typescript
// In agent-state-machine.ts, add transition reason
type TransitionReason = 
  | "user_request"
  | "task_complete" 
  | "error"
  | "ntm_disappeared"  // NEW
  | "poll_failure";    // NEW
```

### Graceful Recovery
Consider adding recovery logic:
```typescript
// If NTM comes back online, could attempt reconnection
async attemptRecovery(agentId: string): Promise<boolean> {
  try {
    const status = await this.ntmClient.getAgentStatus(agentId);
    if (status.alive) {
      // Re-establish polling
      this.startOutputPolling(agentId);
      return true;
    }
  } catch {
    // Recovery failed, agent truly dead
  }
  return false;
}
```

## Testing Requirements

### Unit Tests
1. Test error counter increments on poll failure
2. Test counter resets on successful poll
3. Test threshold triggers markAgentFailed
4. Test poll interval is cleared on failure

### Integration Tests
1. Simulate NTM unavailability (mock returns errors)
2. Verify agent transitions to failed after threshold
3. Verify terminated event is emitted
4. Verify no more polling after failure

### E2E Tests
1. Start agent, then stop NTM
2. Verify Gateway marks agent as failed within ~30 seconds
3. Verify no log spam (warn, not debug for each error)
4. Verify cleanup happens correctly

## Considerations
- **False positives**: Network blips shouldn't kill agents; threshold provides buffer
- **Logging level**: Use "warn" not "debug" so operators can see issues
- **Recovery**: May want to add recovery mechanism for transient NTM issues
- **Consistency**: Same pattern should apply to other drivers with polling

## Definition of Done
- [ ] Error counting implemented
- [ ] Threshold-based failure transition
- [ ] Poll interval cleanup on failure
- [ ] Terminated event emitted
- [ ] Unit tests for error counting
- [ ] Integration tests for threshold behavior
- [ ] E2E test for zombie prevention
